<span class="s1">&lt;h3&gt;</span><span class="s0">Introduction</span><span class="s1">&lt;a </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;headerlink&quot; </span><span class="s2">href</span><span class="s3">=&quot;#introduction&quot; </span><span class="s2">title</span><span class="s3">=&quot;Permalink to this heading&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;</span><span class="s0"></span><span class="s1">&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/h3&gt;</span>
<span class="s1">&lt;p&gt;</span><span class="s0">In the </span><span class="s1">&lt;em&gt;</span><span class="s0">pygame</span><span class="s1">&lt;/em&gt; </span><span class="s0">examples there is a simple example named </span><span class="s4">&amp;quot;</span><span class="s0">chimp</span><span class="s4">&amp;quot;</span><span class="s0">.</span>
<span class="s0">This example simulates a punchable monkey moving around the screen with</span>
<span class="s0">promises of riches and reward. The example itself is very simple, and a</span>
<span class="s0">bit thin on error-checking code. This example program demonstrates many of</span>
<span class="s0">pygame's abilities, like creating a window, loading images and sounds,</span>
<span class="s0">rendering text, and basic event and mouse handling.</span><span class="s1">&lt;/p&gt;</span>
<span class="s1">&lt;p&gt;</span><span class="s0">The program and images can be found inside the standard source distribution</span>
<span class="s0">of pygame. You can run it by running </span><span class="s1">&lt;cite&gt;</span><span class="s0">python -m pygame.examples.chimp</span><span class="s1">&lt;/cite&gt; </span><span class="s0">in</span>
<span class="s0">your terminal.</span><span class="s1">&lt;/p&gt;</span>
<span class="s1">&lt;p&gt;</span><span class="s0">This tutorial will go through the code block by block. Explaining how</span>
<span class="s0">the code works. There will also be mention of how the code could be improved</span>
<span class="s0">and what error checking could help out.</span><span class="s1">&lt;/p&gt;</span>
<span class="s1">&lt;p&gt;</span><span class="s0">This is an excellent tutorial for people getting their first look at</span>
<span class="s0">the </span><span class="s1">&lt;em&gt;</span><span class="s0">pygame</span><span class="s1">&lt;/em&gt; </span><span class="s0">code. Once </span><span class="s1">&lt;em&gt;</span><span class="s0">pygame</span><span class="s1">&lt;/em&gt; </span><span class="s0">is fully installed, you can find</span>
<span class="s0">and run the chimp demo for yourself in the examples directory.</span><span class="s1">&lt;/p&gt;</span>

<span class="s1">&lt;/div&gt;</span>
<span class="s1">&lt;p&gt;</span><span class="s0">This function takes the name of an image to load. It also optionally</span>
<span class="s0">takes an argument it can use to set a colorkey for the image, and an argument</span>
<span class="s0">to scale the image. A colorkey is used in graphics to represent a color of the</span>
<span class="s0">image that is transparent.</span><span class="s1">&lt;/p&gt;</span>
<span class="s1">&lt;p&gt;</span><span class="s0">The first thing this function does is create a full pathname to the file.</span>
<span class="s0">In this example all the resources are in a </span><span class="s4">&amp;quot;</span><span class="s0">data</span><span class="s4">&amp;quot; </span><span class="s0">subdirectory. By using</span>
<span class="s0">the </span><span class="s1">&lt;cite&gt;</span><span class="s0">os.path.join</span><span class="s1">&lt;/cite&gt; </span><span class="s0">function, a pathname will be created that works for whatever</span>
<span class="s0">platform the game is running on.</span><span class="s1">&lt;/p&gt;</span>
<span class="s1">&lt;p&gt;</span><span class="s0">Next we load the image using the </span><span class="s1">&lt;a </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;tooltip reference internal&quot; </span><span class="s2">href</span><span class="s3">=&quot;../ref/image.html#pygame.image.load&quot; </span><span class="s2">title</span><span class="s3">=&quot;&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;&lt;code </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;xref py py-func docutils literal notranslate&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;&lt;span </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;pre&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;</span><span class="s0">pygame.image.load()</span><span class="s1">&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;span </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;tooltip-content&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;</span><span class="s0">load new image from a file (or file-like object)</span><span class="s1">&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/a&gt; </span><span class="s0">function.</span>
<span class="s0">After the image is loaded, we make an important</span>
<span class="s0">call to the </span><span class="s1">&lt;cite&gt;</span><span class="s0">convert()</span><span class="s1">&lt;/cite&gt; </span><span class="s0">function. This makes a new copy of a Surface and converts</span>
<span class="s0">its color format and depth to match the display. This means blitting the</span>
<span class="s0">image to the screen will happen as quickly as possible.</span><span class="s1">&lt;/p&gt;</span>
<span class="s1">&lt;p&gt;</span><span class="s0">We then scale the image, using the </span><span class="s1">&lt;a </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;tooltip reference internal&quot; </span><span class="s2">href</span><span class="s3">=&quot;../ref/transform.html#pygame.transform.scale&quot; </span><span class="s2">title</span><span class="s3">=&quot;&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;&lt;code </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;xref py py-func docutils literal notranslate&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;&lt;span </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;pre&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;</span><span class="s0">pygame.transform.scale()</span><span class="s1">&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;span </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;tooltip-content&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;</span><span class="s0">resize to new resolution</span><span class="s1">&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/a&gt; </span><span class="s0">function.</span>
<span class="s0">This function takes a Surface and the size it should be scaled to. To scale</span>
<span class="s0">by a scalar, we can get the size and scale the x and y by the scalar.</span><span class="s1">&lt;/p&gt;</span>
<span class="s1">&lt;p&gt;</span><span class="s0">Last, we set the colorkey for the image. If the user supplied an argument</span>
<span class="s0">for the colorkey argument we use that value as the colorkey for the image.</span>
<span class="s0">This would usually just be a color RGB value, like (255, 255, 255) for</span>
<span class="s0">white.  You can also pass a value of -1 as the colorkey. In this case the</span>
<span class="s0">function will lookup the color at the topleft pixel of the image, and use</span>
<span class="s0">that color for the colorkey.</span><span class="s1">&lt;/p&gt;</span>

            <span class="s1">&lt;span </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;bp&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;</span><span class="s0">self</span><span class="s1">&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;o&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;</span><span class="s0">.</span><span class="s1">&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;n&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;</span><span class="s0">original</span><span class="s1">&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;o&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;</span><span class="s0">=</span><span class="s1">&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;bp&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;</span><span class="s0">self</span><span class="s1">&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;o&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;</span><span class="s0">.</span><span class="s1">&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;n&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;</span><span class="s0">image</span><span class="s1">&lt;/span&gt;</span>

<span class="s1">&lt;/div&gt;</span>
<span class="s1">&lt;p&gt;</span><span class="s0">The </span><span class="s1">&lt;cite&gt;</span><span class="s0">Chimp</span><span class="s1">&lt;/cite&gt; </span><span class="s0">class is doing a little more work than the fist, but nothing</span>
<span class="s0">more complex. This class will move the chimp back and forth across the</span>
<span class="s0">screen.  When the monkey is punched, he will spin around to exciting effect.</span>
<span class="s0">This class is also derived from the base </span><span class="s1">&lt;a </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;reference internal&quot; </span><span class="s2">href</span><span class="s3">=&quot;../ref/sprite.html#pygame.sprite.Sprite&quot; </span><span class="s2">title</span><span class="s3">=&quot;pygame.sprite.Sprite&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;&lt;code </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;xref py py-class docutils literal notranslate&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;&lt;span </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;pre&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;</span><span class="s0">Sprite</span><span class="s1">&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/a&gt;</span>
<span class="s0">class, and is initialized the same as the fist. While initializing, the class</span>
<span class="s0">also sets the attribute </span><span class="s4">&amp;quot;</span><span class="s0">area</span><span class="s4">&amp;quot; </span><span class="s0">to be the size of the display screen.</span><span class="s1">&lt;/p&gt;</span>
<span class="s1">&lt;p&gt;</span><span class="s0">The </span><span class="s1">&lt;cite&gt;</span><span class="s0">update</span><span class="s1">&lt;/cite&gt; </span><span class="s0">function for the chimp simply looks at the current </span><span class="s4">&amp;quot;</span><span class="s0">dizzy</span><span class="s4">&amp;quot;</span>
<span class="s0">state, which is true when the monkey is spinning from a punch. It calls either</span>
<span class="s0">the </span><span class="s1">&lt;cite&gt;</span><span class="s0">_spin</span><span class="s1">&lt;/cite&gt; </span><span class="s0">or </span><span class="s1">&lt;cite&gt;</span><span class="s0">_walk</span><span class="s1">&lt;/cite&gt; </span><span class="s0">method. These functions are prefixed with an underscore.</span>
<span class="s0">This is just a standard python idiom which suggests these methods should</span>
<span class="s0">only be used by the </span><span class="s1">&lt;cite&gt;</span><span class="s0">Chimp</span><span class="s1">&lt;/cite&gt; </span><span class="s0">class. We could go so far as to give them a double</span>
<span class="s0">underscore, which would tell python to really try to make them private</span>
<span class="s0">methods, but we don't need such protection. :)</span><span class="s1">&lt;/p&gt;</span>
<span class="s1">&lt;p&gt;</span><span class="s0">The </span><span class="s1">&lt;cite&gt;</span><span class="s0">_walk</span><span class="s1">&lt;/cite&gt; </span><span class="s0">method creates a new position for the monkey by moving the current</span>
<span class="s0">rect by a given offset. If this new position crosses outside the display</span>
<span class="s0">area of the screen, it reverses the movement offset. It also mirrors the</span>
<span class="s0">image using the </span><span class="s1">&lt;a </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;tooltip reference internal&quot; </span><span class="s2">href</span><span class="s3">=&quot;../ref/transform.html#pygame.transform.flip&quot; </span><span class="s2">title</span><span class="s3">=&quot;&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;&lt;code </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;xref py py-func docutils literal notranslate&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;&lt;span </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;pre&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;</span><span class="s0">pygame.transform.flip()</span><span class="s1">&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;span </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;tooltip-content&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;</span><span class="s0">flip vertically and horizontally</span><span class="s1">&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/a&gt; </span><span class="s0">function. This is a crude effect</span>
<span class="s0">that makes the monkey look like he's turning the direction he is moving.</span><span class="s1">&lt;/p&gt;</span>
<span class="s1">&lt;p&gt;</span><span class="s0">The </span><span class="s1">&lt;cite&gt;</span><span class="s0">_spin</span><span class="s1">&lt;/cite&gt; </span><span class="s0">method is called when the monkey is currently </span><span class="s4">&amp;quot;</span><span class="s0">dizzy</span><span class="s4">&amp;quot;</span><span class="s0">. The dizzy</span>
<span class="s0">attribute is used to store the current amount of rotation. When the monkey</span>
<span class="s0">has rotated all the way around (360 degrees) it resets the monkey image</span>
<span class="s0">back to the original, non-rotated version. Before calling the</span>
<span class="s1">&lt;a </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;tooltip reference internal&quot; </span><span class="s2">href</span><span class="s3">=&quot;../ref/transform.html#pygame.transform.rotate&quot; </span><span class="s2">title</span><span class="s3">=&quot;&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;&lt;code </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;xref py py-func docutils literal notranslate&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;&lt;span </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;pre&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;</span><span class="s0">pygame.transform.rotate()</span><span class="s1">&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;span </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;tooltip-content&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;</span><span class="s0">rotate an image</span><span class="s1">&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/a&gt; </span><span class="s0">function, you'll see the code makes a local</span>
<span class="s0">reference to the function simply named </span><span class="s4">&amp;quot;</span><span class="s0">rotate</span><span class="s4">&amp;quot;</span><span class="s0">. There is no need to do that</span>
<span class="s0">for this example, it is just done here to keep the following line's length a</span>
<span class="s0">little shorter. Note that when calling the </span><span class="s1">&lt;cite&gt;</span><span class="s0">rotate</span><span class="s1">&lt;/cite&gt; </span><span class="s0">function, we are always</span>
<span class="s0">rotating from the original monkey image. When rotating, there is a slight loss</span>
<span class="s0">of quality. Repeatedly rotating the same image and the quality would get worse</span>
<span class="s0">each time. Also, when rotating an image, the size of the image will actually</span>
<span class="s0">change. This is because the corners of the image will be rotated out, making</span>
<span class="s0">the image bigger. We make sure the center of the new image matches the center</span>
<span class="s0">of the old image, so it rotates without moving.</span><span class="s1">&lt;/p&gt;</span>
<span class="s1">&lt;p&gt;</span><span class="s0">The last method is </span><span class="s1">&lt;cite&gt;</span><span class="s0">punched()</span><span class="s1">&lt;/cite&gt; </span><span class="s0">which tells the sprite to enter its dizzy</span>

<span class="s1">&lt;p&gt;</span><span class="s0">Next we set up the display graphics mode. <span class="s0">window.</span><span class="s1">&lt;/p&gt;</span>
<span class="s1">&lt;p&gt;</span><span class="s0">Last we set the window title and turn off the mouse cursor for our</span>

<span class="s1">&lt;p&gt;</span><span class="s0">As you see, there are a couple steps to getting this done. First we</span>
<span class="s0">must create the font object and render it into a new surface. We then find</span>
<span class="s0">the center of that new surface and blit (paste) it onto the background.</span><span class="s1">&lt;/p&gt;</span>
<span class="s1">&lt;p&gt;</span><span class="s0">The font is created with the </span><span class="s1">&lt;cite&gt;</span><span class="s0">font</span><span class="s1">&lt;/cite&gt; </span><span class="s0">module's </span><span class="s1">&lt;cite&gt;</span><span class="s0">Font()</span><span class="s1">&lt;/cite&gt; </span><span class="s0">constructor. Usually</span>
<span class="s0">you will pass the name of a TrueType font file to this function, but we</span>
<span class="s0">can also pass </span><span class="s1">&lt;cite&gt;</span><span class="s0">None</span><span class="s1">&lt;/cite&gt;</span><span class="s0">, which will use a default font. The </span><span class="s1">&lt;cite&gt;</span><span class="s0">Font</span><span class="s1">&lt;/cite&gt; </span><span class="s0">constructor</span>
<span class="s0">also needs to know the size of font we want to create.</span><span class="s1">&lt;/p&gt;</span>
<span class="s1">&lt;p&gt;</span><span class="s0">We then render that font into a new surface. The </span><span class="s1">&lt;cite&gt;</span><span class="s0">render</span><span class="s1">&lt;/cite&gt; </span><span class="s0">function creates</span>
<span class="s0">a new surface that is the appropriate size for our text. In this case</span>
<span class="s0">we are also telling render to create antialiased text (for a nice smooth</span>
<span class="s0">look) and to use a dark grey color.</span><span class="s1">&lt;/p&gt;</span>
<span class="s1">&lt;p&gt;</span><span class="s0">Next we need to find the centered position of the text on our display.</span>
<span class="s0">We create a </span><span class="s4">&amp;quot;</span><span class="s0">Rect</span><span class="s4">&amp;quot; </span><span class="s0">object from the text dimensions, which allows us to</span>
<span class="s0">easily assign it to the screen center.</span><span class="s1">&lt;/p&gt;</span>
<span class="s1">&lt;p&gt;</span><span class="s0">Finally we blit (blit is like a copy or paste) the text onto the background</span>
<span class="s0">image.</span><span class="s1">&lt;/p&gt;</span>

<span class="s1">&lt;/section&gt;</span>
<span class="s1">&lt;section </span><span class="s2">id</span><span class="s3">=&quot;update-the-sprites&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;</span>
<span class="s1">&lt;h3&gt;</span><span class="s0">Update the Sprites</span><span class="s1">&lt;a </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;headerlink&quot; </span><span class="s2">href</span><span class="s3">=&quot;#update-the-sprites&quot; </span><span class="s2">title</span><span class="s3">=&quot;Permalink to this heading&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;</span><span class="s0"></span><span class="s1">&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/h3&gt;</span>
<span class="s1">&lt;div </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;highlight-default notranslate&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;&lt;div </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;highlight&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;&lt;pre&gt;&lt;span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;n&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;</span><span class="s0">allsprites</span><span class="s1">&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;o&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;</span><span class="s0">.</span><span class="s1">&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;n&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;</span><span class="s0">update</span><span class="s1">&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;p&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;</span><span class="s0">()</span><span class="s1">&lt;/span&gt;</span>
<span class="s1">&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/div&gt;</span>
<span class="s1">&lt;/div&gt;</span>
<span class="s1">&lt;p&gt;</span><span class="s0">Sprite groups have an </span><span class="s1">&lt;cite&gt;</span><span class="s0">update()</span><span class="s1">&lt;/cite&gt; </span><span class="s0">method, which simply calls the update method</span>
<span class="s0">for all the sprites it contains. Each of the objects will move around, depending</span>
<span class="s0">on which state they are in. This is where the chimp will move one step side</span>
<span class="s0">to side, or spin a little farther if he was recently punched.</span><span class="s1">&lt;/p&gt;</span>
<span class="s1">&lt;/section&gt;</span>
<span class="s1">&lt;section </span><span class="s2">id</span><span class="s3">=&quot;draw-the-entire-scene&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;</span>
<span class="s1">&lt;h3&gt;</span><span class="s0">Draw The Entire Scene</span><span class="s1">&lt;a </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;headerlink&quot; </span><span class="s2">href</span><span class="s3">=&quot;#draw-the-entire-scene&quot; </span><span class="s2">title</span><span class="s3">=&quot;Permalink to this heading&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;</span><span class="s0"></span><span class="s1">&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/h3&gt;</span>
<span class="s1">&lt;p&gt;</span><span class="s0">Now that all the objects are in the right place, time to draw them.</span><span class="s1">&lt;/p&gt;</span>
<span class="s1">&lt;div </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;highlight-default notranslate&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;&lt;div </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;highlight&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;&lt;pre&gt;&lt;span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;n&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;</span><span class="s0">screen</span><span class="s1">&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;o&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;</span><span class="s0">.</span><span class="s1">&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;n&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;</span><span class="s0">blit</span><span class="s1">&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;p&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;</span><span class="s0">(</span><span class="s1">&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;n&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;</span><span class="s0">background</span><span class="s1">&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;p&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;</span><span class="s0">,</span><span class="s1">&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;p&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;</span><span class="s0">(</span><span class="s1">&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;mi&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;</span><span class="s0">0</span><span class="s1">&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;p&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;</span><span class="s0">,</span><span class="s1">&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;mi&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;</span><span class="s0">0</span><span class="s1">&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;p&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;</span><span class="s0">))</span><span class="s1">&lt;/span&gt;</span>
<span class="s1">&lt;span </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;n&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;</span><span class="s0">allsprites</span><span class="s1">&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;o&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;</span><span class="s0">.</span><span class="s1">&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;n&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;</span><span class="s0">draw</span><span class="s1">&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;p&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;</span><span class="s0">(</span><span class="s1">&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;n&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;</span><span class="s0">screen</span><span class="s1">&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;p&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;</span><span class="s0">)</span><span class="s1">&lt;/span&gt;</span>
<span class="s1">&lt;span </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;n&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;</span><span class="s0">pg</span><span class="s1">&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;o&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;</span><span class="s0">.</span><span class="s1">&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;n&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;</span><span class="s0">display</span><span class="s1">&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;o&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;</span><span class="s0">.</span><span class="s1">&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;n&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;</span><span class="s0">flip</span><span class="s1">&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;p&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;</span><span class="s0">()</span><span class="s1">&lt;/span&gt;</span>
<span class="s1">&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/div&gt;</span>
<span class="s1">&lt;/div&gt;</span>
<span class="s1">&lt;p&gt;</span><span class="s0">The first blit call will draw the background onto the entire screen. This</span>
<span class="s0">erases everything we saw from the previous frame (slightly inefficient, but</span>
<span class="s0">good enough for this game). Next we call the </span><span class="s1">&lt;cite&gt;</span><span class="s0">draw()</span><span class="s1">&lt;/cite&gt; </span><span class="s0">method of the sprite</span>
<span class="s0">container. Since this sprite container is really an instance of the </span><span class="s4">&amp;quot;</span><span class="s0">RenderPlain</span><span class="s4">&amp;quot;</span>
<span class="s0">sprite group, it knows how to draw our sprites. Lastly, we </span><span class="s1">&lt;cite&gt;</span><span class="s0">flip()</span><span class="s1">&lt;/cite&gt; </span><span class="s0">the contents</span>
<span class="s0">of pygame's software double buffer to the screen. This makes everything we've</span>
<span class="s0">drawn visible all at once.</span><span class="s1">&lt;/p&gt;</span>
<span class="s1">&lt;/section&gt;</span>
<span class="s1">&lt;section </span><span class="s2">id</span><span class="s3">=&quot;game-over&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;</span>
<span class="s1">&lt;h3&gt;</span><span class="s0">Game Over</span><span class="s1">&lt;a </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;headerlink&quot; </span><span class="s2">href</span><span class="s3">=&quot;#game-over&quot; </span><span class="s2">title</span><span class="s3">=&quot;Permalink to this heading&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;</span><span class="s0"></span><span class="s1">&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/h3&gt;</span>
<span class="s1">&lt;p&gt;</span><span class="s0">User has quit, time to clean up.</span><span class="s1">&lt;/p&gt;</span>
<span class="s1">&lt;div </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;highlight-default notranslate&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;&lt;div </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;highlight&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;&lt;pre&gt;&lt;span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;n&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;</span><span class="s0">pg</span><span class="s1">&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;o&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;</span><span class="s0">.</span><span class="s1">&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;n&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;</span><span class="s0">quit</span><span class="s1">&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;p&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;</span><span class="s0">()</span><span class="s1">&lt;/span&gt;</span>
<span class="s1">&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/div&gt;</span>
<span class="s1">&lt;/div&gt;</span>
<span class="s1">&lt;p&gt;</span><span class="s0">Cleaning up the running game in </span><span class="s1">&lt;em&gt;</span><span class="s0">pygame</span><span class="s1">&lt;/em&gt; </span><span class="s0">is extremely simple.</span>
<span class="s0">Since all variables are automatically destructed, we don't really have to do</span>
<span class="s0">anything, but calling </span><span class="s1">&lt;cite&gt;</span><span class="s0">pg.quit()</span><span class="s1">&lt;/cite&gt; </span><span class="s0">explicitly cleans up pygame's internals.</span><span class="s1">&lt;/p&gt;</span>
<span class="s1">&lt;/section&gt;</span>
